00:14:14.540 --> 00:14:18.130
Philosophy aside, there is
this physical human being,

00:14:18.130 --> 00:14:20.540
and there's billions
of them on the planet.

00:14:20.540 --> 00:14:23.720
And one simple way to
think about it is you

00:14:23.720 --> 00:14:26.200
want to hash each person.

00:14:26.200 --> 00:14:27.200
GARY GENSLER: All right.

00:14:27.200 --> 00:14:27.770
We're back.

00:14:27.770 --> 00:14:29.360
We're back to the
hash functions.

00:14:29.360 --> 00:14:30.277
This is good.

00:14:30.277 --> 00:14:32.360
AUDIENCE: But that's
actually what you want to do.

00:14:32.360 --> 00:14:34.910
You want to hash each
person and get a number.

00:14:34.910 --> 00:14:37.370
And the property of that
is that if you come to me

00:14:37.370 --> 00:14:39.000
and I hash you, I
get some number.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:40.875
And if you come again,
I get the same number.

00:14:40.875 --> 00:14:42.680
So I know I'm dealing
with the same person.

00:14:42.680 --> 00:14:44.120
GARY GENSLER: Even
if I put weight?

00:14:44.120 --> 00:14:45.620
AUDIENCE: Even if
you put on weight.

00:14:45.620 --> 00:14:48.295
I can hash because I can
use your iris, let's say.

00:14:48.295 --> 00:14:49.670
Then your twin
brother presumably

00:14:49.670 --> 00:14:50.712
won't have the same iris.

00:14:50.712 --> 00:14:54.270
I'm actually not sure, but
I don't think you will.

00:14:54.270 --> 00:14:56.000
So now a hash you, I
get the same number,

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:56.990
I know who I'm
dealing with, and this

00:14:56.990 --> 00:14:59.115
solves a lot of the problems
in the business world.

00:14:59.115 --> 00:15:03.750
Like KYC, getting a credit card
at a bank, stuff like that.

00:15:03.750 --> 00:15:06.200
And it also solves the problem,
are you a new customer.

00:15:06.200 --> 00:15:10.120
Well, is your hash one of
the new hashes that I--

00:15:10.120 --> 00:15:13.070
is your hash a hash that
I've seen in the past?

00:15:13.070 --> 00:15:15.250
So that's a very simple
way to think of identity.

00:15:15.250 --> 00:15:16.750
And you put philosophy
aside and you

00:15:16.750 --> 00:15:19.900
assume that there is some
physicality of human beings

00:15:19.900 --> 00:15:21.520
that you can distinguish
between using

00:15:21.520 --> 00:15:22.580
a hash function of some sort.

00:15:22.580 --> 00:15:24.038
So the question is
like, how do you

00:15:24.038 --> 00:15:27.190
implement this hash function.

00:15:27.190 --> 00:15:30.080
GARY GENSLER: So
you're not really

00:15:30.080 --> 00:15:31.670
putting philosophy to the side.

00:15:31.670 --> 00:15:35.940
You're saying, that may
be all well and good,

00:15:35.940 --> 00:15:40.020
but you can also take a
physical object, a human,

00:15:40.020 --> 00:15:43.140
apply a hash function,
a cryptographic means,

00:15:43.140 --> 00:15:47.535
and get a unique identifier
for that individual.

00:15:47.535 --> 00:15:49.650
AUDIENCE: I have a
counter question to that.

00:15:49.650 --> 00:15:52.110
So let's say you
hash everything.

00:15:52.110 --> 00:15:55.520
I can have a counter feed
of like five things that can

00:15:55.520 --> 00:15:56.770
essentially be the same thing.

00:15:56.770 --> 00:15:58.853
And you'll just have five
different hashes for it.

00:15:58.853 --> 00:15:59.380
Right?

00:15:59.380 --> 00:16:03.060
It will still have to come from
a non-blockchain source for you

00:16:03.060 --> 00:16:04.570
to be able to--

00:16:04.570 --> 00:16:05.910
AUDIENCE: Well, it's not things.

00:16:05.910 --> 00:16:06.660
It's human beings.

00:16:06.660 --> 00:16:07.450
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:16:07.450 --> 00:16:11.280
But for you to be able
to hash one person,

00:16:11.280 --> 00:16:14.490
you can still reproduce
five other fake people

00:16:14.490 --> 00:16:16.873
and have five different
fake identities

00:16:16.873 --> 00:16:17.790
with a different hash.

00:16:17.790 --> 00:16:20.160
AUDIENCE: So that's
the difficulty, right?

00:16:20.160 --> 00:16:23.945
You can't actually-- if I
hash myself and I get a hash,

00:16:23.945 --> 00:16:25.320
you will have a
lot of difficulty

00:16:25.320 --> 00:16:27.312
producing another human being.

00:16:27.312 --> 00:16:29.520
It's like finding the
collision in the hash function.

00:16:29.520 --> 00:16:32.400
You have a lot of difficulty
producing a human being that

00:16:32.400 --> 00:16:33.870
has the same hash as mine.

00:16:33.870 --> 00:16:35.912
Because the hash function
is collision resistant.

00:16:35.912 --> 00:16:38.820
And it's hard to come
up to clone me 100%.

00:16:38.820 --> 00:16:40.980
For example, my retina,
even if I give you

00:16:40.980 --> 00:16:44.490
all the data behind my
retina and you have it,

00:16:44.490 --> 00:16:47.520
it's very hard to produce
a retina in your own eye

00:16:47.520 --> 00:16:49.870
that you can scan and pretend
to be me, for example.

00:16:49.870 --> 00:16:51.703
That's one way to think
of hashing somebody.

00:16:51.703 --> 00:16:52.880
You just scan the retina.

00:16:52.880 --> 00:16:54.830
And even though you
know the full retina,

00:16:54.830 --> 00:16:57.330
it's of no use to you because
you have to put it in your eye

00:16:57.330 --> 00:16:58.800
and go there and get scanned.

00:16:58.800 --> 00:16:59.830
And it's like, OK, fine.

00:16:59.830 --> 00:17:03.087
Well, our medical
technology is not there yet.

00:17:03.087 --> 00:17:05.504
GARY GENSLER: [INAUDIBLE] And
then we're going to move on.

00:17:05.504 --> 00:17:07.230
AUDIENCE: I'm just going to
say, if you want to take it--

