server and pretend

00:27:06.090 --> 00:27:08.670
to be facebook.com, mess
with the DNS records,

00:27:08.670 --> 00:27:10.500
get you to visit my server.

00:27:10.500 --> 00:27:12.768
When you type www.facebook.com,
you visit my server.

00:27:12.768 --> 00:27:13.560
But you can't tell.

00:27:13.560 --> 00:27:16.010
GARY GENSLER: DNS is
Domain Name Server.

00:27:19.775 --> 00:27:21.150
AUDIENCE: But
anyway, the idea is

00:27:21.150 --> 00:27:22.640
that when you
actually do a look up

00:27:22.640 --> 00:27:24.270
from facebook.com
from an IP address,

00:27:24.270 --> 00:27:25.630
that's actually very insecure.

00:27:25.630 --> 00:27:27.672
And attackers can mess
with that and redirect you

00:27:27.672 --> 00:27:28.770
to their servers.

00:27:28.770 --> 00:27:31.603
And they might completely
replicate the Facebook page

00:27:31.603 --> 00:27:33.770
so you might think you're
interacting with Facebook.

00:27:33.770 --> 00:27:34.220
But you're not.

00:27:34.220 --> 00:27:35.660
You're interacting with
an attacker website.

00:27:35.660 --> 00:27:37.830
And you type in your
password and your user name,

00:27:37.830 --> 00:27:39.000
and then the attacker steals it.

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:40.740
And then he just redirects
you to the real Facebook

00:27:40.740 --> 00:27:42.680
and you won't notice
the attack at all.

00:27:42.680 --> 00:27:43.722
Does that make sense?

00:27:43.722 --> 00:27:45.722
GARY GENSLER: And it all
happens in nanoseconds.

00:27:45.722 --> 00:27:46.870
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:27:46.870 --> 00:27:48.930
And it's called the man
in the middle attack.

00:27:48.930 --> 00:27:51.420
So what you do is you use
public key cryptography

00:27:51.420 --> 00:27:52.590
to solve that problem.

00:27:52.590 --> 00:27:55.030
You say, OK, let's give
each website a key pair.

00:27:55.030 --> 00:27:57.330
So facebook.com will have
a key pair, a secret key

00:27:57.330 --> 00:27:58.560
and a public key.

00:27:58.560 --> 00:28:00.300
So now, the question
is, well, there's

00:28:00.300 --> 00:28:01.900
a public key for
facebook.com, but how

00:28:01.900 --> 00:28:04.358
do you know you have the right
public key for facebook.com.

00:28:04.358 --> 00:28:07.680
Because an attacker could
also give you their public key

00:28:07.680 --> 00:28:08.878
their fake facebook.com.

00:28:08.878 --> 00:28:10.920
So now, how do you
distinguish between those two?

00:28:10.920 --> 00:28:12.920
That's where the certificate
authority comes in.

00:28:12.920 --> 00:28:16.800
So the certificate authority
signs these public keys.

00:28:16.800 --> 00:28:19.380
And you have the public key
of the certificate authority.

00:28:19.380 --> 00:28:21.600
You have a signature from
the certificate authority

00:28:21.600 --> 00:28:23.250
on the public key
of facebook.com.

00:28:23.250 --> 00:28:24.510
You're now ready to
trust that you're

00:28:24.510 --> 00:28:25.950
dealing with the
real facebook.com

00:28:25.950 --> 00:28:28.110
and you can encrypt
your password

00:28:28.110 --> 00:28:30.210
to facebook.com using
your public key.

00:28:30.210 --> 00:28:31.710
There's a lot of
public keys around.

00:28:31.710 --> 00:28:32.630
I know.

00:28:32.630 --> 00:28:34.625
I'm not sure if
