00:28:43.080 --> 00:28:47.310
But know that when Satoshi
Nakamoto wrote that paper,

00:28:47.310 --> 00:28:53.340
she was just using
asymmetric cryptography,

00:28:53.340 --> 00:28:56.460
public-private key cryptography,
that had been invented really

00:28:56.460 --> 00:28:58.470
in the 1970s.

00:28:58.470 --> 00:29:00.450
And then it adopted,
as the internet

00:29:00.450 --> 00:29:06.920
came along, and took off and
had a lot of use in the 1990s

00:29:06.920 --> 00:29:10.020
to secure the internet by 1996.

00:29:10.020 --> 00:29:14.120
And the way that the internet's
secured on TSL and SSL

00:29:14.120 --> 00:29:17.390
and these various
ways it's secured

00:29:17.390 --> 00:29:21.410
was public key-private key
cryptography, a full 12 years

00:29:21.410 --> 00:29:27.050
before Nakamoto wrote the paper,
but used for a different case.

00:29:27.050 --> 00:29:29.360
But Facebook has a public key.

00:29:29.360 --> 00:29:31.700
And all those public
keys of all the websites

00:29:31.700 --> 00:29:36.220
that you visit every day,
there is a central authority

00:29:36.220 --> 00:29:37.600
called a certificate authority.

00:29:37.600 --> 00:29:40.360
There's actually a 100 plus
certificate authorities.

00:29:40.360 --> 00:29:44.320
But certificate
authorities that say,

00:29:44.320 --> 00:29:47.830
this is the Facebook public key.

00:29:47.830 --> 00:29:50.740
So that when you go to your
Facebook or you go to Google

00:29:50.740 --> 00:29:56.440
or you go to shop on Amazon,
you know you're actually--

00:29:56.440 --> 00:30:00.370
so that's a corporate or that's
another form of identity.

00:30:00.370 --> 00:30:04.630
It's not one with
