00:31:56.890 --> 00:32:00.240
So you have, now, two things.

00:32:00.240 --> 00:32:01.770
Let's go back to Bitcoin.

00:32:01.770 --> 00:32:05.470
In Bitcoin transactions,
you have a public key.

00:32:05.470 --> 00:32:08.890
And then somebody
signs a transaction.

00:32:08.890 --> 00:32:12.370
And the math behind it,
the cryptography behind it,

00:32:12.370 --> 00:32:15.280
is a signature and
a public key that

00:32:15.280 --> 00:32:18.740
come from the same private key.

00:32:18.740 --> 00:32:20.990
There's a way to do a
function to check that they

00:32:20.990 --> 00:32:24.390
came from the same private key.

00:32:24.390 --> 00:32:28.320
And the heart and soul of
what was invented in the 1970s

00:32:28.320 --> 00:32:30.900
was not just that there's a
public key and a private key,

00:32:30.900 --> 00:32:34.230
but also that you can
digitally sign it.

00:32:34.230 --> 00:32:36.060
And then when the
digital signature

00:32:36.060 --> 00:32:40.790
is compared to the
public key, it's

00:32:40.790 --> 00:32:44.660
unique if they came from
the same private key.

00:32:44.660 --> 00:32:46.280
So going back to
the New York Times,

00:32:46.280 --> 00:32:49.490
the New York Times you have
both their public key and then

00:32:49.490 --> 00:32:52.310
each headline, each
piece of information

00:32:52.310 --> 00:32:54.900
has a digital signature.

00:32:54.900 --> 00:32:58.290
