to you another place.

00:37:11.110 --> 00:37:15.440
Identity management,
some of the pain points.

00:37:15.440 --> 00:37:16.910
What are we trying to solve?

00:37:16.910 --> 00:37:22.270
And why would blockchain
technology maybe help us out?

00:37:22.270 --> 00:37:25.150
Privacy and security
is a big one.

00:37:28.590 --> 00:37:32.970
There are a lot of
thefts, identity theft.

00:37:32.970 --> 00:37:36.660
How many people are in the room
have had their credit card--

00:37:36.660 --> 00:37:39.660
this year, in 2018,
we're 11 months in--

00:37:39.660 --> 00:37:41.790
have had their credit
card have to be replaced

00:37:41.790 --> 00:37:46.090
because the bank got in touch
and said it's compromised?

00:37:46.090 --> 00:37:47.880
Only about 20% of us.

00:37:47.880 --> 00:37:50.530
I would have thought it
was going to be more.

00:37:50.530 --> 00:37:56.670
I feel like I get one of those
calls every 18 to 24 months.

00:37:56.670 --> 00:37:57.990
Maybe I shop too much.

00:37:57.990 --> 00:38:00.530
Or my daughters are
using my card too much.

00:38:00.530 --> 00:38:03.990
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] big
enough to be a target.

00:38:03.990 --> 00:38:06.962
Student banks tend
to be negative.

00:38:06.962 --> 00:38:10.170
GARY GENSLER: You
think that's it?

00:38:10.170 --> 00:38:14.910
I just assume that some
merchant has been hacked again.

00:38:14.910 --> 00:38:17.880
I mean, every time a
merchant loses 1 million,

00:38:17.880 --> 00:38:22.080
or 100,000, or 50
million accounts,

00:38:22.080 --> 00:38:27.260
then the banking system needs
to send out those notices.

00:38:27.260 --> 00:38:31.820
I chair a commission, Financial
Consumer Protection Commission

00:38:31.820 --> 00:38:32.780
of Maryland.

00:38:32.780 --> 00:38:37.510
And the credit union
advocates in Maryland

00:38:37.510 --> 00:38:41.590
came to our commission and
said, we need some help.

00:38:41.590 --> 00:38:44.660
We banks and credit unions
have to protect a lot of data.

00:38:44.660 --> 00:38:47.410
But every time a
merchant loses data,

00:38:47.410 --> 00:38:49.360
it's us credit
unions and banks that

00:38:49.360 --> 00:38:52.210
have to replace all
the credit cards.

00:38:52.210 --> 00:38:54.520
And they feel there's
an asymmetry, commercial

00:38:54.520 --> 00:38:58.900
asymmetry, that the
banking sector is bearing

00:38:58.900 --> 00:39:04.400
the brunt of other merchant's,
non-financial sectors, data

00:39:04.400 --> 00:39:05.590
breaches.

00:39:05.590 --> 00:39:08.150
And should the state of
Maryland-- this is a live

00:39:08.150 --> 00:39:10.280
issue actually in front
of our commission.

00:39:10.280 --> 00:39:12.350
Should the state of
Maryland change its laws

00:39:12.350 --> 00:39:16.310
to put higher cybersecurity
responsibilities

00:39:16.310 --> 00:39:19.580
on non-financial sector actors?

00:39:19.580 --> 00:39:21.470
And the financial
sector would say, yeah,

00:39:21.470 --> 00:39:24.980
that kind of feels you'd be
leveling the playing field.

00:39:24.980 --> 00:39:26.570
And the merchants
are saying, you

00:39:26.570 --> 00:39:29.950
can't do that on every
grocery store and bar.

00:39:29.950 --> 00:39:36.043
It seems like it's a
little out of sync.

00:39:36.043 --> 00:39:37.460
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I
was going to say

00:39:37.460 --> 00:39:41.700
that credit card theft like this
is a perfect application public

00:39:41.700 --> 00:39:42.950
key cryptography.

00:39:42.950 --> 00:39:47.870
The [INAUDIBLE] don't give
out your credit card number

00:39:47.870 --> 00:39:48.693
to these folks.

